<TITLE> Serbia charges 21 businessmen, officials with graft </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BELGRADE, Nov 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Serbia has charged 21 people, including staff at its tax and trade inspection office, with corruption and abuse of power, the organised crime prosecutor's office said on Friday. They were charged with involvement in a racket in which diesel fuel was imported from Greece, ostensibly for industrial use at a lower tax rate, then sold through a network of filling stations, defrauding the state of $1.7 million. The gang was helped by six trade inspectors who had been brought into the scam by a retired chief inspector, the office said. The deputy director of the tax office's internal audit department also made "significant contributions with his advice, suggestions and interventions", and received a car worth 27,000 euros as a reward, the prosecutor's office added in a statement. Prosecutor's spokesman Tomo Zoric told Reuters 13 suspects were already in custody, two on the run and six free under court monitoring. Serbia has intensified its efforts to fight organised crime and corruption over the last year -- one of its key tasks if it wants to join the European Union. Graft investigations have so far targeted customs and state administration officials, university professors and businessm
